In order that the invention may be more fully understood an embodiment thereof will now be described by way of example with reference to the accompanying drawings, in which:


FIG. 1 is a sectional view through a substrate for use in forming a memory device according to the invention;


FIG. 2 is an electron beam micrograph of a pillar structure for use in a device according to the invention, at a magnification of 60,000;


FIG. 3 is a schematic sectional view of a memory device in accordance with the invention, that utilizes pillars formed as shown in FIG. 2;


FIG. 4 illustrates current-voltage characteristic across the terminals of the device shown in FIG. 3;


FIG. 5 is a plot of the peak current and valley current associated with the relative low and high resistance states of the device shown in FIG. 2, the current being plotted on a logarithmic scale for 50 trials, for two different devices;


FIG. 6 is a graph showing three different conditions of the memory device;


FIG. 6a is a graph of current versus bias voltage for a memory device according to the invention which is initially in a first relatively low resistance state and is then switched to a relatively high resistance state by increasing the bias voltage V;


FIG. 6b corresponds to FIG. 6a and illustrates that the device stays in the relatively low resistance state if the bias remains positive;


FIG. 6c illustrates that when the device is pulsed at -5V for one second, the device returns to its original condition;


FIG. 7 is a graph of the current through the device as a function of time as the device switches between the low and high resistance states;


FIG. 8a illustrates the potential across the diameter of a charging pillar Pch ;


FIG. 8b illustrates the charging potential when a bias voltage V greater than the pillar depletion voltage VD is applied;


FIG. 9 illustrates the level of charge in the charging pillar as a function of applied voltage V;


FIG. 10 is a schematic equivalent circuit diagram of a device in accordance with the invention;


FIG. 11 illustrates schematically a first example of an array of memory devices in accordance with the invention; and


FIG. 12 illustrates a memory cell with an alternative read/write arrangement.
